{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a0d6e285-d5a9-44da-a206-6378f5460ef5","content":"On macOS, when a process crashes the OS automatically generates a **crash report**. You can find it in:\n\n1. **User-level reports:**\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **System-level reports:**\n   ```\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\nLook for files named like `YourAppName_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS versions).\n\nYou can also open **Console.app** → sidebar → **Crash Reports** to browse them with a GUI.\n\n**To get a core dump** instead, run before launching your app:\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\n\nCore files land in `/cores/` (e.g., `/cores/core.<pid>`). Note that System Integrity Protection (SIP) may block core dump generation for some processes.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d9b7dd26-fba1-4278-b3a5-e0f0b8769b35","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question - I don't need to search any codebase for this.","outputTokens":289,"requestId":"2053:37135:73F760:8672EA:69F01195"},"id":"d1cdf6a6-49bf-4f49-be15-6600061f0843","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:47:09.424Z","parentId":"91f5e21f-e117-4049-9dff-8f18437dd68e"}
